mergedYearonYearHospMeans = covid19 %>%
    drop_na(hospitalized) %>%
    select("date","hospitalized") %>%
    mutate(week = week(date),
           year = as.factor(year(date))) %>%
    group_by(year, week) %>%
    summarise_at(vars(hospitalized), list(WeeklyAve = mean)) 

qplot(week, WeeklyAve, data=mergedYearonYearHospMeans, color = year) + xlab("Week of Year") + ylab("Weekly Average Hospitalized")+geom_smooth(span = 0.3, se = TRUE)

#### Fill in covid19
#####################################

covid19 <- read.csv("covid19.csv", 
                    stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
## Fix an error that sometimes comes from importing from EXCEL
names(covid19)[1] <- "date"
# names(covid19)[names(covid19) == "ï..date"] <- 'date'
## Format date column correctly
covid19$date = anydate(covid19$date)
## Check to see if date already has a row in the data, if not add such a row.
if(sum(grepl(date, covid19$date)) == 0){
covid19[nrow(covid19)+1, "date"] = 
  as.character(date)
}
i=as.Date(date)
 # i = as.Date("2022-06-08")
covid19[covid19$date == i,
        c("Bremer.Positive", 
          "Bremer.Recovered",
           "Bremer.Death")]=
    BremerData[BremerData$date==i, 
               c( "Positive",  "Recovered",
                 "Deaths")]

covid19[covid19$date == i,
        c("Butler.P", "Butler.R",
           "Butler.D")]=
    ButlerData[ButlerData$date==i, 
                c( "Positive",  "Recovered",
                 "Deaths")]
covid19[covid19$date == i,
        c("BlackHawk.P", "BlackHawk.R" ,
           "BlackHawk.D")]=
    Black.HawkData[Black.HawkData$date==i, 
                c( "Positive",  "Recovered",
                 "Deaths")]

    # covid19[covid19$date == as.Date(date),"Total.Tested"] = 
    #     Tested[anydate(Tested$date) == date,"Totals"]
    # 
    covid19[covid19$date == as.Date(date),"positive"] = 
        Positive[anydate(Positive$date) == date,"Totals"]
    # covid19[covid19$date == as.Date(date),"Recovered"] = 
    #     Recovered[anydate(Recovered$date) == date,"Totals"]
 OneMonthAgo = closestdate(covid19, 28)
       covid19[covid19$date == as.Date(date),"deaths"] = Deaths[anydate(Deaths$date) == as.Date(date),"Totals"]
 covid19[,"Recovered"] =
     covid19[OneMonthAgo,"positive"] - covid19[OneMonthAgo,"deaths"]

covid19[-1] = sapply(covid19[,-1], as.numeric)
covid19 = covid19 %>%
mutate(Bremer.SS = Bremer.Positive-Bremer.Death - Bremer.Recovered,
Butler.SS = Butler.P - Butler.R,
BlackHawk.SS = BlackHawk.P- BlackHawk.D - BlackHawk.R)

covid19[covid19$date == as.Date(date),"New.Deaths"] = tail(unique(sort(covid19$deaths)),1)[1]-tail(unique(sort(covid19$deaths)),2)[1]

write.csv(covid19, "covid19.csv",row.names = FALSE, na="")

Iowa COVID-19 Summary 2022-12-28

This week we had 2,148 new positive patients (average of 306.9 or 9.7 per 100,000 new positive patients per day). The state is not reporting the number of recovered cases, but it is estimated that we have 12,685 actively sick Iowans. We no longer know the total number of tests each week.

According to HHS, there are 243 (1.9% of active cases) Iowans hospitalized for COVID-19, 239 adults and 3 children. Of those, 21 (8.6% of hospitalized) are in the ICU, 20 adults and 1 children. Hospitals have reported 10 COVID-19 deaths in the last 7 days.

36 deaths in the last week. One in 303 people in Iowa has died of COVID-19.
The newly recorded deaths occurred on 2022-05-25 (1), 2022-11-17 (1), 2022-11-25 (1), 2022-11-28 (1), 2022-11-29 (1), 2022-11-30 (-1), 2022-12-02 (1), 2022-12-03 (2), 2022-12-04 (1), 2022-12-05 (2), 2022-12-08 (1), 2022-12-10 (1), 2022-12-12 (2), 2022-12-13 (2), 2022-12-15 (5), 2022-12-16 (4), 2022-12-17 (1), 2022-12-18 (6), 2022-12-19 (1), 2022-12-20 (2), 2022-12-23 (1)

One year ago, we had 49,796 actively sick and 11,234 new positive patients per day in Iowa.

Two years ago, we had 42,102 actively sick and 535 new positive patients per day in Iowa.
